    "body": "### Problem\n\nHello, after opening [Suckless' Simple Terminal](https://st.suckless.org/) (st), it can display UTF-8 characters properly. However, after opening `nvim`, they are displayed wrong (both within `nvim`, and after exiting to the shell).\n\nFor example, in the bash shell, I can type the accent character `´` followed by `a` to produce `á`. If I then open `nvim`, it is displayed as `Ã¡`. If I close `nvim` and type it again on my shell, I also get `Ã¡`.\n\nSome other useful notes:\n\n- If I use the `reset` command after exiting `nvim`, the issue is fixed.\n- This issue does not happen in `xterm`, but still happens if I run `export TERM=xterm` before running `nvim` in ST.\n- This does not happen with `vim`.\n- This happens in my patched ST version, and with unmodified version 0.8.2. \n- This did not happen some months ago with my patched version, and it definitely did not happen years ago when I started using ST 0.8.2.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Launch ST (vanilla 0.8.2 or modified).\n2. Type `á` in bash shell, renders successfully.\n3. Launch `nvim` 0.11.5 (with or without `--clean`).\n4. Type `á` in editor, renders incorrectly as `Ã¡`.\n5. Exit `nvim`.\n6. Type `á` in bash shell, still renders incorrectly as `Ã¡`.\n7. Run the `reset` command.\n8. Type `á` in bash shell, renders successfully again.\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n1. Launch ST.\n2. Launch `nvim` 0.11.5.\n3. Type `á` in editor, should render successfully as `á`.\n4. Exit `nvim`.\n5. Type `á` in bash shell, should still render successfully as `á`.\n\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.5; Build type: RelWithDebInfo; LuaJIT 2.1.1753364724\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nIssue does not occur with \"vim\" or \"vim -u DEFAULTS\"\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux, kernel 6.16.5\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nSuckless' Simple Terminal (st)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nst-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nArch package manager (pacman)",
